.TH KISSMUX 1 "February 2026" "kissmux" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
kissmux \- KISS device to TCP KISS multiplexer
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B kissmux
[\fB\-listen\fR \fIADDR\fR]
[\fB\-device\fR \fIPATH\fR]
[\fB\-max-frame\fR \fIN\fR]
[\fB\-drop-after\fR \fIDURATION\fR]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B kissmux
owns a single KISS device (e.g. /dev/soundmodem0) and exposes it as a multi-client
TCP KISS hub. Inbound frames from the device are broadcast to all connected clients.
Outbound frames from clients are serialized to the device to prevent interleaving.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.B \-listen
TCP listen address (default :8001).
.TP
.B \-device
KISS device path (default /dev/soundmodem0).
.TP
.B \-max-frame
Maximum KISS payload bytes allowed inside a frame (default 4096).
Oversized frames reset the parser.
.TP
.B \-drop-after
Drop slow clients if writes block longer than this (default 2s).
.SH EXAMPLES
Start a LAN-visible hub on port 8001:
.PP
.RS
kissmux -listen :8001 -device /dev/soundmodem0
.RE
.PP
Bind to localhost only (recommended if you will firewall/port-forward separately):
.PP
.RS
kissmux -listen 127.0.0.1:8001
.RE
.SH NOTES
KISS frames are delimited by 0xC0 and use 0xDB escaping. kissmux does not interpret AX.25/APRS contents.
